nsights from cultural history and gender studies as well as psychoanalytic, narrative, and genre theory, Stern convincingly exposes the foundation of the republic as an unquiet crypt housing those invisible Americans who contributed to its construction.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aemotion, sensation, affect theory, american revolution, literature, theatricality, passion, excess, sentimental novels, sentiment, melodrama, gothic, republic, hate, anger, fear, grief, federalism, mourning, violence, death, war, liberty, freedom, marginalized communities, women, gender, native americans, indigenous, racism, discrimination, poverty, wealth, class, slavery, african-american, counternarratives, nation-building, national identity, legitimacy, authority, nonfiction, narrative, genre, dissent, charlotte temple, coquette, ormond.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1990-1999z978311066785140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226773094423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226773094/original  a978-3-11-066785-1  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1990-1999c1990d1999  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles